<HEADLINE> U.S. Congressional Delegation Visits U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of 14 senior
U.S. Congressional staff members paid a visit to the United
Nations, and exchanged views with senior U.N. officials here on
the U.S.-U.N. ties and the U.N. operations in Kosovo, the Yugoslav
province.
</P>
<P>
This is the second such delegation which toured the United
Nations since May 1999, an event considered by the U.N. and
Congressional staff participants as an important step in binding
the U.S.-U.N. divide.
</P>
<P>
The delegation was organized by the Humpty Dempty Institute
(HDI), a not-for-profit organization with its headquarters in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Ralph Cwerman, HDI president, said, "The institute recognizes
that a robust U.S.-U.N. relations -- one capable of surviving
frank discourse and punctuated policy departures -- requires
trust, engendered through increased interaction and exchange
between the American public policy-makers, and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the largest debtor, has put the United
Nations deep in a financial crisis by owing the world body 1.6
billion U.S. dollars for past and current assessments, two-thirds
of the total dues.
</P>
<P>
Facing possible loss of the U.S. vote in the General Assembly
next year, U.S.-U.N. relations are, in the words of the U.N.
Secretary-General and the U.S. Secretary of State, at a critical
juncture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
