<HEADLINE> EU, Zambia Sign Aid Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
Zambia signed two aid agreements here Friday which amount to a
total of 74 billion kwacha (about 29.6 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Five billion kwacha (about two million dollars) will be
channeled to the Zambia's mining sector and 69 billion kwacha
(about 27.6 million dollars) will be used to upgrade the
Kabwe-Kapiri road in central Zambia.
</P>
<P>
After signing the agreements, Zambian Finance Minister Katele
Kalumba assured the EU that his country will reduce the tariffs of
the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa in full by
October next year.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia will do everything to get access to the balance
of payment support from the EU.
</P>
<P>
He thanked EU for supporting the rehabilitation of the
country's road network, saying road is important to the mining
sector.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that Zambia will host the mining forum for
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) scheduled for
November this year.
</P>
<P>
Jochen Krebs, head of the EU delegation, said he is hopeful
that the money will go toward the complete restructuring of the
mines of Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
