<HEADLINE> Uganda Receives Fund for Hyacinth Removal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
received a total sum of 3.9 million U.S. dollars from Egypt to
help remove water hyacinth in the Kiyoga Lake in the central part
of the country.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Andruale Awuzu, Minister of State for
Works, when he met the parliamentary committee on natural
resources here Friday, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
The fund would not be scattered into several departments. It
would only be used by the Ministry of Works, Housing and
Communications, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The lake, which provides drinking water for all the neighboring
 districts, has been blocked by water hyacinth, plant leaves and
soil.
</P>
<P>
Water blockade had caused flooding to several districts,
stripping those who live by fishing of their sole means of
livelihood.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian government sent a team of experts to Uganda in
1998 to help remove the water plant from Lake Victoria, the
world's second largest fresh water lake.
</P>
<P>
River Nile is a lifeline for all those living nearby. The
Egyptian government has been greatly concerned about the quality
of water in the river, especially in the source of the river.
</P>
</TEXT>
