<HEADLINE> Conference on AIDS in Africa to Be Held in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Over 4,000 delegates have
registered to take part in the forthcoming 11th International
Conference on AIDS and STDs (sexually transmitted diseases) in
Africa scheduled for September 12-16 in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the organizing committee available here Friday
showed that by August 12, the closing date of registration for the
conference, about 3,500 international delegates and 1,500 Zambian
participants are expected to attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
Connie Osborne, member of the organizing committee for the
conference, said the committee has made adequate accommodation
arrangements for the delegates and ruled out any problems arising
from lack of accommodation during the conference.
</P>
<P>
The Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) estimates
that globally there are 33 million HIV infected adults and
children out of which 22 million are in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The conference, according to the committee, will serve as a
vehicle and platform for Africa to revitalize and expand the
response to the HIV/AIDS epidemic, and also provide an opportunity
to review the past efforts with a view to providing alterative and
more effective strategies to the fight against the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the delegates will comprise researchers,
political leaders, representatives from communities, people living
with HIV/AIDS and policy makers from Africa and rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the conference is "looking into the future:
Setting Priorities for HIV/AIDS in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
