<HEADLINE> British MP Optimistic for Solution of Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A British parliamentarian
expressed optimism here on Friday that there is likelihood that
the long-standing division of the Cyprus island be resolved.
</P>
<P>
Eddie O'Hara, speaking on behalf of visiting British MPs after
meeting with Cyprus' Parliament Speaker Spyros Kyprianou, also
stressed that any solutin to the issue must safeguard the unity of
Cyprus, the return of all refugees to their homes, freedom of
movement and should be based on a bizonal, bicommunal federation.
</P>
<P>
"We are heartened that recently, the G-8 group (the seven most
industrialized nations plus Russia) countries have expressed
their concern that the Cyprus issue has gone unresolved for 25
years," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on June 20 at the end of their annual
summit in Cologne, Germany, the leaders of G-8 urged the Greek
and Turkish Cypriots to enter talks without setting any
pre-conditions and negotiate in good faith until a settlement is
reached.
</P>
<P>
O'Hara said that any solution of the Cyprus issue "must be
based on one Cyprus people, both Turkish Cypriots and Greek
Cypriots, one Cypriot nationality, one Cypriot state, one island
of Cyprus with one international identity."
</P>
<P>
On his part, Kyprianou said efforts for a solution must
forcus on averting anything that could consolidate the current
division and Turkish occupation of the island's northern part.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that things on Cyprus issue may get a
turn for the better but also warned of more difficult times
ahead.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
</TEXT>
