<HEADLINE> UNHCR Sees 750,000 Kosovo Albanians Returning Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Three quarters of a
million Kosovo Albanians have returned to homeland since the
return of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR) to Kosovo two months ago, a U.N. spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Less than 50,000 Kosovo Albanians are still in neighboring
countries in the region, the U.N. agency said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 91,000 who were evacuated to 29 different countries
during the 78-day U.S.-British air-strikes against Yugoslavia from
March 24 to June 12, nearly one third have returned, UNHCR
estimated.
</P>
<P>
However, in the past two months of UNHCR presence in Kosovo,
around 130,000 Serbs and Roma fled Kososvo to other parts of
Serbia and Montenegro, brining to 180,000 the number of
non-Albanians displaced from Kosovo, according to UNHCR figures.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said UNHCR is deeply concerned
about the security situation of Serbs in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Since there have numerous incidents of murder and Serbs have
been forced out of their homes, Eckhard said, it would not be
possible for UNHCR to encourage Serbs to return to their homes
until adequate levels of security exist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
