<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Coffee Production Affected by Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia loses 30 percent of
its total coffee production annually due to coffee-bean disease, a
senior official of the Trade and Industry Ministry said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The disease mainly affects coffee beans grown in rainy areas of
the country, Brook Debebe, deputy minister of the ministry, told a
seminar on coffee-bean disease.
</P>
<P>
He said a considerable amount of coffee plantation had been
protected from the disease by applying 15 types of
disease-resistant coffee beans in coffee producing areas over the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia, one of the third largest coffee producers in Africa,
has been making efforts to increase its coffee production by
popularizing improved coffee variety.
</P>
<P>
With more than 300,000 hectares of acreage under coffee,
Ethiopia produces about 250,000 tons coffee annually, one third of
which are for export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
