<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The volume of Egyptian exports during the first nine
months of the fiscal year 1998/1999 amounted to 3 billion
U.S. dollars, the Arab daily Al Hayat reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The United States is ranked as the biggest importer of Egyptian
goods, followed by the European Union (EU) countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU ranks as the biggest exporter to Egypt, and the U.S. the
second.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egypt's total exports to Russia and the Commonwealth
of Independent States stood at 24 million dollars, to Arab states
at 405 million dollars, to Afro-Asian countries at 328 million
dollars and to Australia 3 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Bank deposits of Lebanon's private sector stood at
1.1 billion U.S. dollars during the first six months of this year,
said a report by Lebanon's Francebank.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed a slowdown in bank deposits of the
private sector to such factors as the stalled Middle East peace
process, Israel's continuing aggressions against Lebanon and the
oscillation and repercussions of the domestic political factors,
weakening overall economic performance, the Arab daily Al Hayat
Friday quoted the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt signed a contract with two companies - one Dutch
and the other Danish for the construction and management of a
containers station in East Port Said.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal El-Ganzouri said after the
signing ceremony Wednesday that Egypt adopted the BOT system in
implementing projects in the fields of electricity, transport,
road construction and other utilities.
</P>
<P>
He added that Egypt had spent 1.5 billion Egyptian pounds (430
million U.S. dollars) on building a waterway to East Port
Said.
</P>
<P>
The containers station will cost 480 million dollars of which
40 percent will be undertaken by the Egyptian side and the Dutch
and Danish companies 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
The docks of the new containers station will be 2,400 meters
long and will handle 2.5 million containers a year. The digging
of a 2,200 meter-long waterway is currently under way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
