<HEADLINE> Egypt, S.Africa Endeavor to Promote Bilateral Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and South Africa are to
hold the fourth session of a joint ministerial commission in
October to seek ways of further promoting economic and trade
cooperation between the two sides, a trade official said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The annual session, to be held in South Africa's economic and
commercial center of Johannesburg, will be co-chaired by Egyptian
Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili and South African
Minister of Trade and Industry Alec Erwin, said Alaa Khalil, head
of the Egyptian Trade Representation Authority.
</P>
<P>
It will also discuss the implementation of the agreements and
recommendations reached during the previous session and the
obstacles hindering bilateral cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
The third session of the commission was held last October in
Cairo, during which the two sides signed three deals on trade,
promotion and reciprocal protection of investments, merchant
shipping and related maritime matters.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also initialed an agreement on security
cooperation and memorandum of understanding on cooperation in
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Egypt and South Africa stood at about
60 million U.S. dollars in 1997. The goods traded between the two
sides include oil and oil products, chemicals, metals, textiles,
agricultural products, machines and handicrafts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
