<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Nuclear Ships Pass S. African Coastline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The two British ships
carrying nuclear fuel from France to Japan rounded the Cape coast
between Wednesday and Thursday and were well clear of the South
African coast, Pretoria's navy spokesman Glen Knox said Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said the navy was not tracking the vessels, the Pacific
Pintail and the Pacific Teal, because they were so far out.
</P>
<P>
"The closest they came to our coastline was 320 miles but they
stayed outside the country's exclusive economic zone (EEZ)," Knox
said.
</P>
<P>
The ships are carrying about 450 kgs of mixed oxides of uranium
and plutonium fuel.
</P>
<P>
"We had one vessel on standby in case they entered our waters
but they were well out of the EEZ. They had no influence on us.
</P>
<P>
"They reported their positions when they approached our
coastline and we plotted the route they followed," Knox said.
</P>
<P>
He said the two vessels could have come to within 12 nautical
miles of the coast if they had wanted to under international
maritime law but they had adhered to a request by the government
to stay out of South Africa's territorial waters and its larger
marine EEZ.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a delegation from the African National Congress in
the Western Cape said it had met Environmental and Tourism
Minister Valli Moosa on Thursday to raise its concerns about the
shipments.
</P>
<P>
Moosa assured the delegation that the government was
investigating the issue of nuclear shipments and was currently
developing further policy, ANC spokesman Max Ozinsky said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Ozinsky said the Western Cape ANC's main concern was that the
two ships had the right to enter South African waters without
informing the government.
</P>
<P>
The company responsible for the fuel was not prepared to give
the government an assurance that the ships would not enter South
Africa's EEZ, Ozinsky said.
</P>
<P>
"We are also concerned at reports that a further 10 shipments
will be rounding the Cape every year."
</P>
<P>
Last month environmental group Greenpeace International called
on South Africa and all coastal nations on the route of the
shipment to oppose the transport, while environmental groups
protested outside the French, British and Japanese embassies in
Cape Town on August 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
