<HEADLINE> Lebanon Concerned about Indian-Pakistani Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon Friday expressed deep
concern over the latest military confrontation between India and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"We feel sorry very much for the human casualties from India
and Pakistan and call on both sides to exercise restraint,"
Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss said in a news conference.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the two countries solve their
existing disputes through dialogue and related international laws.
</P>
<P>
Tensions soared between Islamabad and New Delhi after Indian
fighter jets shot down a Pakistani military aircraft on Tuesday,
killing all 16 crew members.
</P>
<P>
After the attack, the troops along the border of the two
countries went on high alert.
</P>
<P>
India accused the Pakistani plane of crossing into its air
space while Pakistan argued its aircraft was inside its own
air space when it was attacked.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan fought three wars during the last 50
years over their disputes in Kashmir, an area both countries
have claimed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
