<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stepashin, Primakov Agree to Work Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Former Russian prime ministers
Sergei Stepashin and Yevgeny Primakov have agreed "on the forms
and plans for cooperation and the coordination of their work," the
Interfax news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
They reached this agreement during a three-hour one-on-one
meeting Thursday at Primakov's country home, Interfax said,
quoting sources close to Stepashin.
</P>
<P>
"Stepashin continues active consultations," the sources said,
adding that in the several days following his dismissal last
Monday, he has discussed Russia's political situation with no less
than 80 percent of the country's provincial leaders.
</P>
<P>
"By Monday, he will make a decision concerning his political
future," the sources said. "The decision will be coordinated with
key political forces. All his efforts will be directed solely at
preventing the further exacerbation of the political and economic
situation," they said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, Stepashin said that he lost his job, less than
three months after taking over from Primakov last May, because he
had "never wanted to be anyone's servant."
</P>
<P>
"No one has ever bought me. It cannot be true, after all, that
everything can be bought and sold in our country," Stepashin said
in an interview with the Russian daily Komsomolskaya Pravda.
</P>
<P>
He last met with President Boris Yeltsin early Monday in the
presidential country residence near Moscow, when he got the final
word that he was fired.
</P>
<P>
"I think this was a very difficult decision for him to make,"
Stepashin said, referring to Yeltsin's decision to oust him. But
he hinted that somebody in the Kremlin entourage was behind his
demise.
</P>
<P>
"When I arrived in Gorki early in the morning, he was not
alone. That is enough evidence that he needed some kind of support
to make the decision," Stepashin said, noting that he had not
expected to be fired.
</P>
<P>
"On Thursday (August 5) I had a preliminary conversation with
the president. And after that really wonderful conversation with
Boris Nikolayevich -- it had been a long time since we talked like
that and understood each other like that -- I left for a very good
trip to some Russian regions -- at his advice, by the way.
</P>
<P>
"And when I came back, I wasn't really ready for such a turn of
events as on Monday," Stepashin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
