<HEADLINE> China Smashes Netherlands at World Women's Volleyball GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Local favourites China lived up
expectations when they came from one set down to outclass the
Netherlands 29-31, 25-23, 25-15, 25-23, here Friday at the opening
day of the 1999 World Women's Volleyball Grand Prix Macao Leg.
</P>
<P>
"The Netherlands played a big game tonight," said Chinese head
coach Hu Jin who earlier coached Chinese national team between
1989 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
"But finally we had the game of the night," Hu added. "After we
trailed one set, our players showed their strength to pick up the
confidence to beat them out."
</P>
<P>
After levelling five times, world runners-up China opened a big
lead in the first set at 21-18 with solid defence and powerful
offence.
</P>
<P>
But the Dutch spikers, who finsihed fifth in Atalanta Olympic
Games, came back to overtake the led at 23-22, 24-23 and 26-25
mainly due to errors from the Chinese and their own powerful
spikes. They finally sealed the tough set at 31-29.
</P>
<P>
At 8-12 in favour of the Netherlands in the second, the fast
Chinese fought back for another see-saw game. After a series of
successive blocks, the Chinese clinched the set at 25-23.
</P>
<P>
With the ability of defense and block and quick changes in
tactics, the Chinese dominated the third before the Dutch fought
back again in the fourth, with the two teams exchanging lead
before the Chinese chalked up the match at 25-23.
</P>
<P>
In another match Friday, Brazil did not meet much resistance
from the Italians, winning in consecutive sets 25-20, 25-17, 25-20.
</P>
<P>
There are four legs in this year's tournament with world top
eight women's teams involved. Apart from the above four teams,
Cuba, Russia, South Korea and Japan are competing simultaniously
in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The eight teams then were re-grouped and contest in Chinese
Taipei and the Phillipines respectively in the following weekend.
</P>
<P>
The first three teams will join hosts China to vie for the
title at the Grand Prix finals in Yunnan, China at the end of the
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
