<HEADLINE> Scholars Condemn Lee's Separatist Remark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Scholars in east China's Fujian
Province strongly condemned Lee Teng-hui's "two states" statement
and told Lee that his only way out is to return to the "One China"
stand.
</P>
<P>
Wu Nengyuan, head of the Taiwan Institute of the Fujian
Provincial Academy of Social Sciences, said at a forum that Lee
and the Taiwan authorities' peddling of the separatist remark is
the most serious incident in the cross-Strait relations in decades.
</P>
<P>
The statement constitutes a grave challenge to the peaceful
reunification of the motherland, undermining the foundation of
cross-Strait relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Lee, in pursuing his own ambition, gambles with
the security and welfare of the 21 million people of Taiwan, an
act that has aroused the utmost indignation of the entire Chinese
people.
</P>
<P>
Yang Huaji, of the academy, said that since 1988, more than 200
Taiwanese scholars have visited the academy, which has also sent
27 scholars to Taiwan to conduct academic exchange.
</P>
<P>
"These exchanges have facilitated further cross-strait academic
exchanges and are conducive to the peaceful reunification of the
motherland," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lee's "two states" statement is groundless from any
perspectives, and is totally unacceptable to people of the
academic circles across the straits, he said.
</P>
<P>
Many other scholars also expressed their indignation and
condemned Lee's separatist remark at the forum held in this
capital city of Fujian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
