<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebels Cease Fire Temporarily for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Congolese rebels fighting to
oust president Laurent Kabila have declared a seven-day cease-fire
to allow the anti-polio vaccination campaign to go smoothly,
rebels sources in eastern Congo said.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire was effective at mid-night Friday and will go
on for a week, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) in Goma Emile
Ilunga said that this halt of hostilities was a humanitarian
gesture, but had nothing to do with the Lusaka July 10 cease-fire
agreement his group has so far refused to endorse.
</P>
<P>
A small hitch had occurred on Thursday when Ugandan troops had
 impounded a cargo plane chartered by the WHO carrying 400,000
doses of vaccine at Buta airport on claims that it had not sought
landing clearance first.
</P>
<P>
"They should let this plane unload the medicine, otherwise it
will expire," Moise Nyarugabo, the RCD-Goma Vice-President told
RNA Thursday. But the plane was later allowed to discharge the
cargo.
</P>
<P>
In rebel-controlled territory, the operation began at 10:00
a.m. local time. In Goma, a high turn-out has been noted, rebel
sources in the area have announced.
</P>
<P>
''We love Congolese children, we want all of them to be
vaccinated,'' Nyarugabo said. Up to 10 million Congolese children
are expected to benefit from the anti-polio vaccination campaign.
</P>
<P>
The operation is likely to face constraints relating to
communication problems as the road and rail-way networks in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo are in a shambles or have
collapsed after many years of mismanagement which characterized
the regime of late dictator Mobutu Sese Seko. Air transport is
going to play a key role in helping U.N. workers to carry out the
operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
