<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Sentenced to Life Imprisonment in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The three were part of a group of 17 genocide suspects from
Rushashi and Musasa commune who had been jointly tried by the
Rushashi court, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Four of the suspects were sentenced to jail terms ranging from
five to 25 years, while five others who were found guilty of theft
and destruction of property, were requested to pay compensation to
the victims.
</P>
<P>
Five other suspects were released after the court found them
not guilty of charges. The 1994 genocide in Rwanda claimed the
lives of more than half a million people, mostly ethnic Tutsis and
Hutu moderates.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan prisons are crammed with over 124,000 genocide
suspects most of whom are waiting for trial. Since the beginning
of genocide trials in December 1996, Rwandan criminal courts have
judged over 1,500 cases, with over 300 death penalties handed
down.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda is looking for alternatives to speed up trials of
genocide suspects, in resorting to traditional courts called
''Gacaca'' in the country which are due to begin in the year
2,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
