<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Engaging Britain on Gold Sales: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa was making
headway in its dealings with Britain on how to minimize the
negative effects of the planned sale of half its gold reserves,
Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Phumzile Mhlambo-Ngcuka said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There is an ongoing dialog between us and that country, and we
 believe it is going to pay off," South African Press Association
quoted her as telling parliamentarians in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
She welcomed the International Monetary Fund's (IMF) decision
to review its plans to sell off 10 percent of its gold reserves.
Such a move would harm several undeveloped countries which export
gold, including South Africa, the world's largest gold producer,
she said.
</P>
<P>
"Thank God reason has triumphed in the IMF," she said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF had planned to sell one million ounces of gold to fund
debt relief, but said last month other mechanisms would be
considered.
</P>
<P>
Mhlambo-Ngcuka said the government felt if gold sales were used
to finance debt relief, it would have the effect of replacing
trade with aid.
</P>
<P>
She said South Africa was not trying to stop others from
selling their gold reserves, but wanted a reliable mechanism that
would minimize any harmful effects, to be put in place.
</P>
<P>
The minister said it would be premature for gold mining
companies to plead poverty at this stage and start laying off
workers. However, it was too early to start celebrating a revival
in the gold price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
