<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Togo to Intervene in Liberia-Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and Togo have launched a
joint diplomatic initiative to douse the escalating tension
between their west African neighbors, Guinea and Liberia, over the
recent abduction of six foreign hostages within Liberian
territory.
</P>
<P>
A high-level official of the Nigerian Foreign Ministry said
here Friday in capital Abuja that a Nigerian delegation would
visit both countries to try to encourage dialog in resolving their
current conflict.
</P>
<P>
Tension between the two countries rose after the abduction of
western aid workers by rebel gunmen in an area where Liberian
government troops are fighting Guinea-based rebels. Liberia has
been accusing Guinea, its northern neighbor, of harboring
"dissident forces" whom it blamed for the abduction.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Liberia has lodged a protest with the United
Nations Security Council against its fellow member of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), which has responded by
placing its troops in Liberia in alert.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, a group calling itself the "Joint Forces for the
Liberation of Liberia" reportedly prevented 100 aid workers from
escaping the unrest in northern Liberia to safety in Guinea.
</P>
<P>
But Nigerian Foreign Ministry said Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo and the chairman of the 16-member ECOWAS, Gnassingbe
Eyadema of Togo, were determined to ensure the increasing rhetoric
against unrest did not degenerate.
</P>
<P>
"Both presidents are working to ensure the fragile peace
secured for the sub-region with the July 7 peace plan between
rebels and the government in Sierra Leone marked the beginning of
an era of peace for the sub-region," said the foreign ministry
official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
