<HEADLINE> Kenya's Payment Balance Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya said
here Friday that the country's overall balance of payments was a
deficit of 63 million U.S.dollars in June 1999 compared to a
deficit of 194 million dollars in June of last year.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly report, the central bank said the improvement in
the payment balance is a result of good performance in the capital
account, offsetting the widening in the current account.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the current account deficit widened by
194 million dollars to 332 million in the 12 months to June 1999
from 138 million dollars in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The bank noted that the country's trade deficit widened as
exports declined and imports rose and there was also a fall in
services account surplus.
</P>
<P>
The capital account improved with a surplus of 269 million
dollars at the end of June as against a deficit of 56 million
dollars a year ago, the report said, adding that there was also
an increase in long-term capital inflows while long-term capital
outflows decreased.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign exchange reserves in Kenya fell to 969 million
dollars or 3.7 months of import cover at the end of June, 1999,
from 1.083 billion dollars, or to 4.2 months of import cover in
the same period last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, official foreign exchange reserves stood at 657
million dollars down from 771 million dollars last year, and
commercial banks' foreign exchange reserves remained at 312
million dollars, the same as in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
