<HEADLINE> Kenya's Public Debt More Than Half of GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's public debt was 476.4
billion shillings (about 6.44 billion U.S. dollars), or 64.4
percent of its gross domestic product, at the end of June,
according to a Central Bank of Kenya report available here Friday.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly report for August, the central bank said the
figure was 1.1 billion shillings ( around 15 million dollars) less
than that for the same time in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Domestic debt accounted for 150.3 billion shillings (2.03
billion dollars) while external debt amounted to 326.1 billion
shillings (4.41 billion dollars)," it said.
</P>
<P>
The amount of the external debt registered a drop of 5.8
billion shillings (78.4 million dollars) from June 1998.
</P>
<P>
External debt service in 1998/99 (July/June) amounted to 28.4
billion shillings (450.7 million dollars) compared to 29.2
billion shillings (395 million dollars) in 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said domestic debt had increased 4.8 billion
shillings (65 million dollars) compared to that in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
Most of the new debt had accumulated in the process of
servicing external debt and meeting government budgetary
requirements, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
