<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All English Pregnant Women to Have HIV Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- All pregnant women in England are
to be offered HIV test in an effort to reduce the rising number of
babies born with the deadly virus.
</P>
<P>
The tests are to be recommended to women as part of their
routine ante-natal screening, but there will be no element of
compulsion, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
The measures, announced on Friday by Health Minister Tessa
Jowell, are designed to cut by 80 percent the number of babies
born HIV positive by the year 2002. They are also aimed at
improving treatment for women with HIV.
</P>
<P>
Women known to be HIV positive can take anti-viral drugs during
pregnancy to minimize the risk of transmitting the disease to
their babies during birth. At the moment, two-thirds of the women
who are HIV positive do not know they are infected.
</P>
<P>
The UK has one of Europe's highest maternal HIV transmission
rates. In 1997, 265 mothers in the UK were HIV positive and as a
result about 50 babies were born with the virus.  
</P>
</TEXT>
