<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Pumped Up By U.S. PPI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets closed
higher Friday, lifted by a lower-than-expected 0.2 percent rise in
the July U.S. producer price index.
</P>
<P>
The UK's FTSE 100 index, which had been trading down 24 points
before the release of the U.S. producer price figures, rebounded
to close up 1.49 percent, or 91.8 points, at 6,245.1.
</P>
<P>
Strong support came from Wall Street where the Dow index was up
around 135 points as the London session ended its third successive
positive close.
</P>
<P>
The rise by the FTSE 100 came in the wake of a 138-point jump
Thursday, and again featured strong gains in the heavyweight bank,
telecom and pharmaceutical sectors.
</P>
<P>
But dealers attributed much of the strength in the big three
sectors to traders and short-term investors who were looking to
close short positions.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, talk of a possible merger in the banking sector
and receding interest-rate fears spurred a buying spree on the
electronic Xetra Dax, which closed up 1.79 percent, or 92 points,
at 5,219.43.
</P>
<P>
Commerzbank gained 8.17 percent after a media report that
contact with BfG Bank could lead to Commerzbank's purchase of the
bank.
</P>
<P>
BHF Bank, listed on the MDAX, gained 29.39 percent as Dutch
financial group ING made an offer for outstanding shares in the
bank.
</P>
<P>
Paris's blue chip CAC 40 closed up 1.5 percent Friday, boosted
by more positive signals on the U.S. economy after weaker than
expected PPI data cheered Wall Street and soothed some inflation
worries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
