<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abortion Still Banned in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's top health official
Friday confirmed that abortion is illegal except under
exceptional circumstances such as when the health of the mother
was in danger.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary for the Health Ministry Julius Meme made
the remarks in a bid to defuse the growing row over his earlier
statements on possibility to legitimatize abortion.
</P>
<P>
Pro-life activists had regarded such a signal as an apparent
government acknowledgment that abortion was acceptable and
strongly opposed it.
</P>
<P>
The Catholic Church, which has many followers in Kenya, is
opposed not only to abortion but also to the use of
contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
Meme reaffirmed the government's position that abortion could
be effected only if the attending doctor deemed the health of the
mother to be is in danger.
</P>
<P>
"Such abortion," he said, "can then be carried out in a
licensed health facility."
</P>
<P>
Media reports here said a majority of doctors at an on-going
seminar in the country's Eastern Province suggested abortion ought
to be legalized while some opposed it, saying it was tantamount to
murder.
</P>
<P>
Each year a lot of Kenyan women die of abortion-related
complications because abortion is illegal and the women dare not
to go to hospitals but turn to quacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
