<HEADLINE> Crude Oil on New Two-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil prices rallied to a
22-month peak of 21 U.S. dollars a barrel Friday, buoyed by
Nigerian supply disruption, declines in U.S. oil stockpiles and
OPEC output restraint.
</P>
<P>
London September futures for Britain's Brent crude touched the
psychological 21 U.S. dollar level, its highest since October 9,
1997, before dropping back to 20.88 U.S. dollars for a 39 cent
gain.
</P>
<P>
The price of oil is more than double the historic lows touched
at the turn of the year following disciplined reductions in supply
under a market rescue accord by the Organization of the Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said data this week from the United States showing
falling inventories of crude and petroleum products had underlined
the success of OPEC producers in tackling a glut which early this
year dragged Brent below 10 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil stocks in the United States, the world's largest
consumer, now are 6 percent lower than a year ago while gasoline
inventories are 4 percent smaller, according to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
The price drew more immediate strength Friday from news that
oil major Texaco declared force majeure on some Nigerian oil
exports, meaning it cannot guarantee meeting all of its sales
commitments, due to community unrest in the Niger Delta.
</P>
<P>
Output curbs implemented by OPEC after a meeting in the Hague
in March are expected to erase excess inventories entirely in
coming months.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, traders are concerned that prices may be due for
a reverse after the heavy gains of recent weeks, Reuters said.
</P>
<P>
"Scepticism has emerged about future price trends which we
attribute to concern that OPEC will raise its production at the
September 22 meeting," Reuters quoted Merrill Lynch as saying in a
note to clients. "We continue to believe that this will not occur
and that OPEC will reaffirm its commitment to the Hague
agreement."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Venezuelan Energy and Mines Minister Ali Rodriguez
said he did not expect any change in OPEC's production policy when
the group meets next month. The cartel has agreed to maintain
supply curbs for a year until the end of March which may leave a
shortfall in supplies during winter months.
</P>
<P>
The Paris-based International Energy Agency said earlier this
week that world oil demand was expected to accelerate next year,
while only marginal extra supplies would emerge from non-OPEC
producers.
</P>
<P>
A recovery in Asian economies would help double global demand
growth from 900,000 barrels a day this year to 1.8 million bpd in
2000. It expected only 660,000 bpd of extra non-OPEC supply, it
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
