<HEADLINE> Ivanov Warns Against Support to Terrorists in Daghestan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov said on Saturday that terrorists in the republic of
Daghestan are trying to impose anti-constitutional order and any
outside support to them will be considered as "glaring
interference" in Russia's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov made the warning in a special message to U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan, the foreign ministers of the G-7
industrialized countries, and other member states of the
Commonwealth of Independent States, the European Union, the
Organization of the Islamic Conference and some Islamic countries,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said "there are indisputable facts indicating that the
terrorists are getting financial, material and other assistance
from outside.
</P>
<P>
"Any form of support for the terrorists' actions will be
considered as a glaring interference in the internal affairs of
the Russian Federation with all the consequences it entails,"
Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the international community
understood the situation.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorism is a global deadly challenge, and much has already
been done in the fight against it in order to consolidate efforts
within the framework of the U.N., the G-8, the CIS and other
international organizations," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian authorities have launched a massive campaign
against the Islamic militants who have infiltrated a number of
Daghestani villages near the republic of Chechnya a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The air force, interior troops, elite special police squads,
and armed volunteers were involved in the operations, which have
reportedly caused panic among the rebels and forced them to
abandon some villages they seized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
