<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Urges KFOR to Halt Violence Against Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The international peace-keeping
force in Kosovo (KFOR) must step up measures to prevent brutal
acts of violence against Serbs, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The situation is made more serious by what the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees' (UNHCR) has called a "systematic
campaign" of violence and brutality, Dini said in an interview
with Rome's daily La Republica.
</P>
<P>
KFOR has been hampered in its efforts to control the situation,
Dini said. He also pointed a finger at the slow selection
procedure for the special United Nations police force that is
being assembled to take over law and order duties in the province.
</P>
<P>
Dini denied rumors of a split between certain European nations
and the U.S. on the future status of Kosovo and NATO's involvement
in the transition phase.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, UNHCR declared that the escalating violence
against Serb residents of Pristina, the Kosovo capital, has
reduced their numbers from 20,000 to less than 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Instances such as the shooting of two women, aged 70 and 79, in
their homes Monday night are signs of a growing tide of violence
aimed at driving the remaining Serbs out of the province with a
majority of ethnic Albanians, Dini noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
