<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Cleaning Up of U.S. Rivers, Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- In his weekly radio address
Saturday, U.S. President Bill Clinton urged the Environmental
Protection Agency to work together with states to clean up the
nation's most polluted rivers and lakes.
</P>
<P>
Clinton ask them first to identify the most polluted waters and
then to develop strong, enforceable plans to restore the rivers
and lakes to health.
</P>
<P>
This is a continuation of work begun in 1972 with passage of
the federal Clean Water Act. The goal of the latest cleanup plan
is water clean enough for swimming or fishing, the president said.
</P>
<P>
About 40 percent of the nation's waterways do not meet the
swimming or fishing test. According to a study by states and the
EPA, about 20,000 polluted waterways fail to meet the standard.
This includes about 300,000 miles of rivers and shoreline and
close to 5 million acres of lakes. It was reported that recently
half a million of fishes in Potomac River have been killed by the
polluted water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
