<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wildcat Well in Tibet Gushes Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A wildcat well in the Luenpola
Basin of the Tibet Autonomous Region gushed crude oil this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The region's first commercial flow of crude oil was announced
July 9 in the same basin, in the northern part of the "Roof of the
World", according to the China National Star Petroleum Corporation
(CNSPC), which is in charge of the exploration.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 tons of high-temperature steam was pumped into
the No.1 Luenpola wildcat well, which is 4,700 m above sea level,
from July 26 to August 11, and after 60 hours of well sealing, oil
began to gush out, CNSPC Vice-President Zhou Baixiu said.
</P>
<P>
The successful trial exploration has proven more than three
million tons of oil reserves, indicating a medium-sized oilfield
with some 10 million tons of reserves, he said, adding that his
company will test a third wildcat well in September.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said that the latest development is of great
significance for the social stability and economic development in
Tibet, a region traditionally short of energy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Ban 75 Illegal Drug Bazaars By October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- China plans to clamp down on 75
illegal medicine trading bazaars nationwide by October.
</P>
<P>
In a massive drive to regulate the country's medicine market,
related departments at various levels are asked to start a ban on
illegal purchases and trading of medicines and the traditional
Chinese herbal medicines, and traders without licenses.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Xiaoyu, director of the State Drug Administration, told a
conference held here today that China has made progress in this
respect in the past few months. For example, 22 illegal drug
outlets had been shut down in central China's Hunan Province alone,
and 1,442 individual traders without licenses were punished, Zheng
added.
</P>
<P>
Zheng said that the focus of the work in the latter half of
this year is to abolish illegal drug markets and curb fake drug
products in order to protect the consumers' interests.
</P>
<P>
He urged local authorities to strictly follow the country's
regulations and laws on medicine dealings, and make sure that the
75 illegal drug bazaars are closed down by this October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
