<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Unions Slammed for Forming Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Federation of Trade
Unions Saturday accused the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions of
ditching the workers by turning into a political party.
</P>
<P>
The federation said in a statement that the unfortunate part
was that the congress was using membership fees to launch the
party.
</P>
<P>
"Trade union subscriptions paid by members of the unions are
meant for membership service. It is going to be a serious problem
when the resources are used for political purposes," said the
federation.
</P>
<P>
The congress announced early this year that it was turning into
a political party to challenge the ruling party in the year 2000
parliamentary elections and the presidential elections coming up
in the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
The federation said the workers should reject the idea since no
 referendum was held on the issue.
</P>
<P>
"It is the duty of each individual subscriber to rise and
resist the misuse of his or her subscriptions," said the
federation.
</P>
<P>
Recently, there were reports that some unions affiliated to the
congress were on a collision path with the mother body warning it
to desist from pursuing a political agenda. 
</P>
