<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diaries Expose Japanese Aggressors' Atrocities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Three diaries depicting the
Japanese aggressors' atrocities during the Nanjing Massacre 60
years ago were contributed today to the Memorial Hall for the
Victims of the Nanjing Massacre in this capital of east China's
Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The diaries, written by Sun Jichang, a Chinese secretary to the
German ambassador to China from 1937 to 1940, depict in detail the
horrible casualties inflicted upon the people of Nanjing by the
Japanese troops in their attack against the city from August to
December in 1937.
</P>
<P>
According to the diaries, when the Japanese troops occupied
the city, Sun and other embassy workers retreated to a ship on the
Yangtze River, and he saw all the houses along the river ablaze
and the whole city red with flames, and refugees streaming out.
</P>
<P>
Experts have confirmed that Sun's depictions of this major
historical event conform to the historical records.
</P>
<P>
Sun died in 1992, at the age of 92, and his diaries were
contributed to the memorial hall by his nephew, Sun Jinming, a
retired official, at a seminar held here today on new findings
concerning the Nanjing Massacre.
</P>
<P>
At the seminar, Zhao Jianmin, a history professor at Shanghai-
based Fudan University, said that he has confirmed that the
Japanese troops confiscated 880,000 volumes of books from
libraries in Nanjing during their occupation.
</P>
<P>
Historians from Japan also displayed evidence confirming the
Japanese troops' massacre of ordinary Chinese citizens in the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Seeks Foreign Investment to Promote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has turned to independent
power producers (IPPs) built with foreign investments in an effort
to meet the rising demand for electricity in recent years, an
economic weekly has reported.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of the Middle East Economic Digest (MEED) said
demand for electricity increases by 7-8 percent annually in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Egypt began resorting to foreign-funded IPP projects in
mid-1990s when the country could no longer rely on itself to
finance the new electricity projects, said the London-based
magazine which focuses on reporting Mideast economy and business.
</P>
<P>
The first such project entails the addition of two 340-megawatt
(MW) units to the Sidi Krier power station, west of the
Mediterranean port city of Alexandria, 220 kilometers northwest of
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
A group led by InterGen of the United States has signed with
the Egyptian Electricity Authority (EEA) all the relevant
contracts for the 480-million-U.S.-dollar project, whose
engineering and procurement work has been going ahead smoothly.
</P>
<P>
ABB Alstom Power, a company recently formed by Zurich-based ABB
Asea Brown Boveri and France's Alstom, is to supply the turbine
generators, and Babcock &AMP; Wilcox of the U.S. will provide the
boilers for the plant.
</P>
<P>
The plant, due for completion at the start of 2001, will be
constructed in the build-own-operate-transfer (BOOT) system. The
EEA is to pay for the power that InterGen produces at 0.026
dollars a kilowatt-hour (kWh).
</P>
<P>
Egypt has offered to Electricite de France (EdF) next two IPP
schemes, involving 650-MW plants at Suez and East Port Said, two
cities at the southern and northern ends of the Suez Canal, MEED
said.
</P>
<P>
The next IPP project is expected to be a 650-MW plant for Sharm
el-Sheikh, a Red Sea resort in southern Sinai, for which bids are
expected to be invited internationally towards the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
About 10 more IPPs have been listed by EEA to be issued for
foreign bid up to 2005, the magazine said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
