<HEADLINE> HK Sinfonietta to Present "The Sound of Mother Nature" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Sinfonietta, an
orchestra characterized by talented young local musicians, will
present a concert with the theme "The Sound of Mother Nature".
</P>
<P>
The concert, conducted by Tsung Yeh and with Timothy Landauer
as cellist, will be staged at 8 p.m. on September 11 and 12
respectively at the auditoriums of Tai Po Civic Center and Tsuen
Wan Town Hall.
</P>
<P>
The program includes "Man Ching" (world premiere) by So Ting
Cheong, "Pezzo Capriccioso, Op.62" by Tchaikovsky, "Ga Da Mei Lin
Cello Concerto" (Hong Kong premiere) by Wang Qiang and "Symphony
No.6 in F, Op.68 Pastorale" by Beethoven.
</P>
<P>
Striving to achieve the goal to establish as a high-standard
local orchestra for the promotion of classical music, the Hong
Kong Sinfonietta, formed in 1990, has held more than 90 concerts
in addition to professional support to other local performing
groups.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, more than 45 local composers' works have
been presented by the orchestra with over half being premiere. In
the 1999 season, with Tsung Yeh as music director, the orchestra
is striving for being the second professional orchestra in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Tsung Yeh received his "Academic Excellence Award" upon
graduation from the Mannes College of Music in New York before his
pursuit of a master degree at the Yale University in 1983. There
he studied conducting with Max Rudolf, Leonard Slatkin and Murry
Sidlin. At present, he is also music director of the Sound Bend
Symphony Orchestra and the North West Indiana Symphony Orchestra
in the United States. 
</P>
