<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Courts Reign in Somali Capital After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Normalcy returned to Hodon
district, South Mogadishu, late Saturday morning after heavy
fighting between the forces of the Islamic courts and freelance
armed gangs Friday evening and early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to Abdunasir Dahir Mohamed, one of the courts'
officials involved in the fighting, their forces had been provoked
by what he called elements trying to destabilize the security of
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The fighting broke out Friday evening after residents of the
district tried to establish an Islamic court of their own to
improve the security in their residential areas as well as
restoring the rule of law. The existing Islamic courts
immediately reacted by offering a battle wagon and several heavily
armed militiamen to safeguard what would be the new Islamic court
headquarters in Hodon district.
</P>
<P>
Fighting resumed early Saturday morning with the two sides
exchanging heavy gunfire.
</P>
<P>
There are no exact casualty figures available. However,
officials from the Islamic courts said two of their men were
wounded during the fighting Saturday morning and one of their
fighters died late Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The gunfire exchange subsided at about 9:00 a.m. local time
Saturday morning with the freelance armed gangs were defeated and
chased away deep into Bermuda area, the most dangerous part of the
capital in the heart of the city.
</P>
<P>
Abdunasir Dahir Mohamed told reporters that his forces have
achieved a victory against the bandits and would teach a similar
lesson to whoever tries to undermine their activities.
</P>
<P>
With the absence of a central administration in Mogadishu, the
Islamic courts now remain the most powerful and united force
existing in the capital following the collapse of the Libya and
Egypt-sponsored administration of Mogadishu announced by some of
the city's warlords including Ali Mahdi Mohamed and Hussein Aidid.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic courts are trying to spread their influence
steadily and control the capital and even the southern regions. In
this endeavor, the Islamic courts also seem to be gaining more
support and popularity since the areas under their control are
relatively bandits free.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, unlike the armed clashes with the involvement of the
factional leaders, no lootings or killings of clan affiliations
have taken place when the Islamic courts are involved in any armed
confrontations against any group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
