<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Golkar May Review Presidential Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's ruling Golkar Party
said Saturday that it was not impossible that the party reviewed
incumbent President B.J. Habibie's nomination as the candidate for
the next president if there were no enough support from other
parties to back Habibie.
</P>
<P>
"We hope other parties will give support (to Habibie). But if
only, I repeat, if only support that we expect cannot be reached,
perhaps we will make review. But it is just in case 'if only.' We
of course keep struggling to make success," Golkar General
Chairman Akbar Tanjung said at a seminar here.
</P>
<P>
The Golkar has nominated Habibie for the 1999/2004 term of
presidency. Habibie is in competition with Megawati Soekarnoputri,
leader of the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P)
which won this year's June 7 election with a relative majority.
</P>
<P>
Akbar, whose party took second place in the election, was still
optimistic that the Habibie bid would succeed and get support from
other parties and factions in the People's Consultative Assembly
(MPR), which will meet in November to elect the country's next
president.
</P>
<P>
"But we are still optimistic that we have enough chance to win
the presidential race," Akbar added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that his party would make deal with other parties
to find a way to strengthen the composition of the next
administration.
</P>
<P>
"If our candidate is elected, we may propose other parties be
accommodated in the next administration," he said.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Chairman of the National Awakening Party (PKB)
Matori Abdul Djalil Saturday reiterated his support to Megawati.
</P>
<P>
"We should give a priority to the winner of election. The party
is PDI-P. So give priority to Megawati to race in the presidential
election next November," Matori said in a seminar here.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's highest decision-making body, will
comprise members of the House of Representatives plus 200
appointed regional and interest groups' representatives. The House
itself will have 500 members, 462 of whom will come from the 48
political parties that contested the June 7 election. The
remaining 38 members will be military personnel and policemen
appointed by the Armed Forces leadership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
