<HEADLINE> Nigerian Defense Minister Resigns on "Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper Saturday quoted a government source as
saying that it was unclear about the nature of the illness but one
source said recently, "he had been unable to sustain
conversations for long."
</P>
<P>
The former army chief who was flown abroad for medical
attention in June was reported then to be suffering from a
psychological disorder described as clinical depression.
</P>
<P>
He hurriedly returned to the country to beat the deadline for
the screening of ministerial nominees by Nigeria's Senate which
has unanimously approved his nomination.
</P>
<P>
On assumption of duty as defense minister, Danjuma promised to
ensure that during his tenure, the military institutions would be
rid of political soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"My first priorities will be to cleanse the armed forces,
especially the army and militarize the military," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the inauguration of the new government on May 29 this
year, Obasanjo has carried out two principal reforms in the armed
forces. The first was the retirement of service chiefs and then
the retirement of about 200 officers of the army, navy and air
force.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's Punch newspaper quoted sources as saying President
Obasanjo was deeply affected by the Danjoma's resignation and
immediately tried to persuade him to reconsider his decision
because of the negative effect the resignation may have on his
administration.
</P>
<P>
Apart from summoning the defense minister, the sources said,
the president also contacted Danjoma's close associates to join in
the bid to prevail on him to shelve the idea.
</P>
<P>
One source said, "if he sticks to his guns as he would like do,
it will be a big blow to the young government. Defense is not
just any other ministry. It is a sensitive portfolio. That was
probably why the president was jolted and began immediate
consultations to find the best way to handle the situation."
</P>
</TEXT>
