<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Legislators Net in Furniture Allowance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Against widespread public protest,
members of the National Assembly or parliament started collecting
cheques Friday for their own furniture allowance which was also
proposed for Senators.
</P>
<P>
However, Senate President Evan Enwerem warned Friday in Benin,
Edo State, against what he called "excessive demands for personal
comfort" by the legislators, which he said were being used as a
tool for blackmail by "the enemy within", said the Guardian
newspaper Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Besides, their behavior could send the wrong signals to people
opposed to democracy, he added.
</P>
<P>
Enwerem reminded members of the House of Assembly that only
negative reports are carried about them in the press and warned
that "we could unwittingly destroy ourselves in this way."
</P>
<P>
The senate president urged the state lawmakers to be wary of
forces of destabilization within their midst.
</P>
<P>
The cheques were cleared by the National Assembly bureaucrats
Thursday, the day the allocation of their quarters by balloting
was done.
</P>
<P>
A member of the House of Representatives who preferred not to
be named lamented that people from his constituency had been
sending signals for their own share of the furniture largesse
since last week, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The government, after hot debate, agreed last week to pay each
member of the 109-member Senate 3.5 million naira (about 37,000
U.S. dollars) and their counterpart in the 360-member House 2.5
million naira (26,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The decision ignited strong protests throughout Nigeria when
the west African nation is currently under-going severe financial
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
