<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Leader Stresses Constitutional Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said here Saturday that opening-up the ownership of land
and public utilities to foreigners will not only boost technology
transfer but also open up new markets for Philippine products both
at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly television program, Estrada said that once
foreigners are allowed to own lands and certain public utilities,
factories will be built and jobs will be generated, thus his
country will be exporting products and not contract workers.
</P>
<P>
"Products will be manufactured here, and we can reduce the
number of overseas contract workers going abroad because they will
now be working here, and we are going to export products instead
of workers," the president said.
</P>
<P>
At present, about 4 million Filipinos are working in 182
countries and regions in the world, and they earn the country 6
billion to 7 billion U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Estrada is campaigning for charter changes, which, he said, are
aimed at accelerating economic reforms in the country.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, foreigners' ownership of land
and public utilities is limited to no more than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, opposition forces have accused the president of trying
to extend his six-year term by amending the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the same program, Finance Secretary Edgardo
Espiritu allayed fears that the economic reforms envisioned by the
president in the new constitution would result in unlimited
exploitation of the nation's natural resources to the disadvantage
of the Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
He said the underlying objective of the proposed new economic
nationalism of attracting foreign investments is to hasten the
country's development and in the process, uplift the living
conditions of the people, especially the poor.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Jose Pardo of the Department of Trade and Industry,
who was also a guest in the TV program, said that in the past
years the Philippines lagged behind in economic growth compared
with its neighbors, which allowed foreigners to own lands for
industrial, and even for agricultural use.
</P>
<P>
He said the latest available figures in 1997 showed that
Indonesia got 4.7 billion dollars in direct foreign investments,
Malaysia 3.8 billion dollars, Thailand 3 billion dollars, and the
Philippines only 1.2 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
