<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belfast Parade Marches On After Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A traditional Protestant
Apprentice Boys' parade marched down the main nationalist Lower
Ormeau Road in Northern Ireland's capital of Belfast on Saturday
without major incident after police removed sit-down protesters.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of protesters who had planned to block the Protestant
march were carried away by officers as police cleared half the
road shortly after 5:30 a.m.(0430 GMT). Nineteen police officers
and a number of protesters were injured.
</P>
<P>
During the parade, bottles were thrown, but none of the
marchers were injured.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's main parade, which took place in the Northern
Ireland city of Londonderry, known as Derry to its largely
Catholic population, involved up to 10,000 marchers and 150 bands.
It is also facing nationalist protests by residents from the
Catholic Bogside area.
</P>
<P>
Both parades were given the go-ahead by the Northern Ireland
Parades Commission.
</P>
<P>
The religious leaders have appealed for calm during the marches,
which take place on the eve of the first anniversary of a car bomb
in the town of Omagh that killed 29 people and wounded hundreds
more on August 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Parades by the Protestant Orange Order and the Apprentice Boys
have been the subject of controversy for many years in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The marchers view the parades as a traditional expression of
their culture, but in Catholic nationalist areas they are often
viewed as triumphalist and intimidating.
</P>
<P>
The two parades are to commemorate the 1689 Siege of Derry,
when Protestant apprentices shut the gates of the walled city
against the forces of the Catholic King James II in December 1688.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Protestants died before the city in that war and
Londonderry is now 75 percent Catholic.
</P>
<P>
The peace process in Northern Ireland is deadlocked due to a
long-running dispute between politicians from the majority
Protestant and minority Catholic communities over guerrilla
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the Irish Republic are currently seeking ways to
revive last year's Good Friday peace accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
