<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pinochet to Fight Extradition to Spain: Son </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Former Chilean leader Augusto
Pinochet intends to fight extradition from Britain to Spain where
he suspects he would not get a fair trial, his son said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Marco Antonio Pinochet told BBC that his 83-year-old father
would not go to Madrid voluntarily to face charges of human rights
abuses.
</P>
<P>
He said his father, who is currently under house arrest outside
London, is in poor health. He said he is worried that his father
might die in custody.
</P>
<P>
"Go direct to Spain? No. We think we have to keep to the
process that has already started," Pinochet's son said.
</P>
<P>
"In Spain he is already judged. It would not be a fair trial in
Spain," he said.
</P>
<P>
A number of Chilean military officials are now in Britain to
see Pinochet. They will meet him together with his Spanish lawyers,
"and discuss what they have to do in case he has to go to Spain,"
the son said.
</P>
<P>
"We are very worried that during the process, which could last
a long time -- I don't know how long -- he might die because his
health could further deteriorate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet was arrested in a London hospital last October while
he was recovering from a minor operation. A Spanish judge has
accused Pinochet of being responsible for the deaths and
disappearances of more than 3,000 people. The judge has also asked
Britain to extradite Pinochet to Spain to face trial.
</P>
<P>
Though Pinochet has denied the charges, Britain is scheduled to
begin the extradition proceedings on September 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
