<HEADLINE> Canada Targeted For U.S. Drug Blacklist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department is
recommending that Canada be added to a drug blacklist, a list on
which Panama, Colombia and Mexico have already been identified, "
the Globe and Mail" said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation will go to U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. She will decide on whether or not to seek approval from
President Bill Clinton on the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented U.S. action has provoked alarm and a flurry
of diplomatic activity among senior Canadian officials in an
attempt to contain an escalating battle between the two
neighboring countries, the newspaper added.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to "shame" Canada into waking up and taking necessary
actions, U.S. State Department officials recently informed Ottawa
about their serious concern over the drug problem, according to
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
U.S. intelligence reports suggest the amount of heroin and
marijuana moving through Canada into the United States has reached
alarming proportions, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
