<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rainstorm Inflicts Heavy Casualties on Central China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A rainstorm that has been
battering Chenzhou City in central China's Hunan Province since
Thursday has caused inconvenience to more than 1.4 million people
and caused 1.5 billion yuan in direct economic losses.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures indicate that more than 100 people have been
killed or gone missing in the flood caused by the rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
The flood also destroyed more than 30,000 dwellings, inundated
nearly 40,000 ha of cropland and seriously damaged the city's
infrastructure facilities, with the Chenzhou section of the
Beijing-Guangzhou Railway blocked for 19 hours.
</P>
<P>
During the period from 8:00 am Thursday to 8:00 am Friday, 295
mm of rain was recorded, accounting for one third of the annual
average.
</P>
<P>
The Hunan provincial government has sent three battalions of
militia, reserve forces and armed police to Chenzhou, and 44,000
of the 120,000 people stranded by the flood have been evacuated.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the flood has retreated from the
urban areas, and road transportation, power supply and
telecommunications have basically been restored. 
</P>
</TEXT>
