<HEADLINE> Today's Diplomatic News Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tajikistan President Emomali Rakhmonov wound up his four-day
goodwill visit to China and left the Chinese capital for home this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
His entourage, including Foreign Minister Talbak Nazarov, also
left aboard the same plane.
</P>
<P>
China's Vice-Foreign Minister Wang Yingfan and Chinese
Ambassador to Tajikistan Fu Quanzhang saw Rakhmonov and his party
off at the airport.
</P>
<P>
China Resents U.S. Government's Allowing the Dalai Lama
</P>
<P>
Trip
</P>
<P>
China has voiced its strong resentment and firm opposition to
the U.S. government for allowing the Dalai Lama to visit the
United States, Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Dalai Lama's recent trip to New York, Zhu
said China has already made a solemn representation to the U.S.
side.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is an inalienable part of the Chinese territories, and
the Tibet issue is entirely China's internal affairs, which brooks
no interference from any foreign country, Zhu said, adding that
the Dalai Lama is not merely a religious figure but a "political
exile" engaged in the activities of splitting China. 
</P>
