<HEADLINE> Kenyan Minister Blasts Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Francis
Masakhalia has said the biggest challenge in luring investors to
Kenya is its image which has been dented by corruption.
</P>
<P>
He noted it had to improve Kenya's image for creating an
enabling environment for investment as he addressed the opening of
a two-day annual seminar of the Institute of Certified Public
Secretaries of Kenya Friday in Mombasa, a sea port in southeastern
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard Saturday quoted the minister as
saying that to deal with corruption, every Kenyan should take it
upon him or herself to improve governance which requires
accountability and transparency in the management of economic
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Saying it took two to tango, Masakhalia stressed that the fight
against corruption must target both the giver and the receiver.
</P>
<P>
He noted that organizations should put in place internal
control to facilitate early detection of corruption practices
perpetrated by their employees.
</P>
<P>
The minister also warned that Kenyans should stop accusing one
another over the country's plight to protect the country's
interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
