<HEADLINE> Bank Indonesia Governor Hopes Rupiah to Strengthen Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia Governor Sjahril
Sabirin Saturday expressed his hope that the rupiah can again
strengthen next week after a week-long weakening following the
Bank Bali scandal which rocked the country's banking sector.
</P>
<P>
"God willing, the rupiah's value will rebound after undergoing
fluctuations in the past few days," Sabirin told reporters
following a meeting with President B.J. Habibie here.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah closed at 7,930/7,980 per U.S. dollar in the
interbank spot market here Friday, 70 points down from the
previous day's closing at 7,860/7,910 per U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin said the rupiah was ideally traded at the level of
6,000 to 7,000, but it had weakened to almost 8,000 rupiah against
the greenback in the past week.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah had weakened following the alleged criminal action
in an interbank transaction between publicly listed Bank Bali and
the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA).
</P>
<P>
The two institutions, Bank Bali and IBRA, had allegedly
committed a criminal act which also involves a member of the
ruling Golkar Party's central executive board.
</P>
<P>
Bank Bali allegedly paid Golkar's Deputy Treasurer Setyo
Novanto and other businessmen related to Golkar some 550 billion
rupiah (80.87 million U.S. dollars) in commission for recovering
904.6 billion rupiah (about 133 million dollars) in interbank
credits.
</P>
<P>
Habibie had pledged that the government will probe into the
scandal that rocked Bank Bali. 
</P>
</TEXT>
