<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Allows Foreign Tourists to Buy Tax-Free Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Foreign tourists visiting
Thailand will be allowed to buy locally-made automobiles with tax
exemption and lower prices, a senior Finance Ministry official
said here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai News Agency quoted Somchainuek Hengtrakul,
director-general of the Customs Department, as saying that given
the tax exemption, automobiles purchased under the scheme would be
60 percent cheaper than those sold on the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourists could then drive the cars to travel in the
country and even drive out to neighboring countries which have
road-links with Thailand, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"The scheme is initiated by the Customs Department and will be
proposed to the cabinet soon, if approved, it will be launched in
November, making Thailand the first ASEAN country to do so," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Somchainuek said that the initiative, similar to that earlier
introduced by the European Union, is aimed at promoting "Made in
Thailand" products and boosting Thai exports.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourists could either ship the purchased cars back to
their countries, or sell them to local buyers, who would then have
to pay full tax and other fees as those sold on the domestic
market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
