<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Govt Urged to Lift Ban on Gypsum Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi cement producers have
urged the government to withdraw a ban on the import of gypsum, a
raw material for cement, saying that otherwise the country's
fast-growing cement industry may face a crisis due to the ban.
</P>
<P>
The cement industry in the country has achieved a remarkable
growth as a result of increasing domestic demand during the last
decade, the Independent daily newspaper said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The cement production capacity now stands at about 3 million
tons against that of only 200,000 tons in 1972, and the present
demand is about 6 million tons, leaving a shortfall of 3 million
tons per annum, the Cement Manufacturers Association was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2004, Bangladesh will become self-sufficient in
cement, and if trade negotiations with neighboring countries go in
the right direction, the cement industry is likely to emerge as a
new export sector.
</P>
<P>
If the ban on the import of gypsum is not withdrawn
immediately, it is feared that cement production will suffer and
lead to higher import of cement, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Board of Investment has already recorded registration of 35
factories with a capacity of about 14 million tons, of which 15
have already gone into operation while three more will go into
production soon.
</P>
<P>
Besides, 10 factories with 100-percent foreign investments will
also go into production by the year 2002, while eight with a
production capacity of 4 million tons of 100 percent local
investment are at the early stage of construction. If all the
approved projects go into production by the year 2004, the cement
sector will need about half a million tons of gypsum annually.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh produces gypsum as a by-product, and it is used as
soil fertilizer. Gypsum is also used for producing cement and
accounts for 5 percent of the raw material.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture has estimated that 200,000 tons of
gypsum will be needed for the farm sector while the cement sector
has a current demand of about 150,000 tons against the local
availability of 200,000 tons, leaving a shortfall of 150,000 tons.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
