<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Upsetted by Italy at Women's Volleyball GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Italy pulled off an upset victory
over World runners-up China 3-0 here on Saturday at 1999 World
Women's Volleyball Grand Prix Macao Leg.
</P>
<P>
The scores are 29-27, 26-24 and 27-25, which marked the first-
ever victory for Italy over China since they beat China 3-2 at the
same tournament two years ago in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
While Italian head coach Angiolino Frigoni kept calm over the
win, saying "Today's victory doesn't mean tommorow's win", his
Chinese counterpart Hu Jin acknowledged that "the Italians played
better than us today."
</P>
<P>
Hu explained that China suffered the defeat mainly due to
unforced errors and low successive percentage of first offence.
</P>
<P>
He admitted the defeat suggested China's arch-rivals were not
only those traditional ones such as Cuba, Russia and Brazil, but
also Italy, the Netherlands, Croatia and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
World number fifth Italy, where volleyball is the most
practised women sport, looked in top form for a steady performance
as they fought back from behind in three sets to win the crucial
points respectively.
</P>
<P>
China opened a good start by leading to 19-16, but were blocked
by the Italians at the net, conceding the lead to 24-23. After
saving four set points, the Chinese lost the set at 29-27.
</P>
<P>
After leading at 22-20 in the second set, China was again
stopped from the brink of the victory as the Italians caught up to
level the score at 24-24 and kept the winning rhythm for two big
points with powerful spikes and an block-out from the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the third set, the two teams exchanged the
leads till the score deadlocked at 19-all.
</P>
<P>
The more powerful and steady Italians then took three points in
a row, and increased their advantage to 24-21.
</P>
<P>
The fighting Chinese saved three match points and came back to
overtake the lead at 25-24. At the crucial point, the Italians'
spikes told everything that the Chinese could not cope with. They
took three points consecutively, sealing the match in 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
In another game on Saturday, three-time winner Brazil showed
their superority of firm defence and powerful spikes and totally
controlled the game from the very beginning, finishing the match
25-18, 25-17 and 25-20 over the Netherlands in just 70 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"The reason we lost so easily is that we are too tired today
because yesterday's match against China was finished too late, "
said Dutch head coach Pierre Mathieu.
</P>
<P>
Asked for the prospect on Sunday's match against China,
Brazilian head coach Bernardo Rocha de Rezende said: "It is going
to be a tough one."
</P>
<P>
He added that China was not as strong as last year because they
were testing now. "We have to play better than today so that we
can have chances to beat them."
</P>
<P>
Italy is to meet the Netherlands on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
