<HEADLINE> African Leaders Urged to Stop Sending Youngsters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Young Africans Welfare
Association (YAWA) has called on African leaders to stop sending
youngsters to the battle front in the continent.
</P>
<P>
During the young people's pan-African consultative conference
held in Lusaka Friday, the association expressed concern at the
number of young people who are dying in armed conflicts currently
ravaging the continent of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Ireen Lungu, chairperson of the association's University of
Zambia branch, was quoted by Saturday's Times of Zambia newspaper
as saying at the conference that young people in Africa had great
potential to develop their continent, and peace was a prerequisite
to sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Young people required good quality education, health care,
employment and other social amenities for them to fully exploit
their potential and contribute to the socio-economic development
of Africa, she noted.
</P>
<P>
She also said young people should have their human rights such
as freedom of expression guaranteed including their right to life
and development.
</P>
<P>
At the same function, President of the association Aalgernon
Situla expressed concern at the number of innocent and potentially
productive young people dying in wars being perpetrated by some
African leaders.
</P>
<P>
African countries should give young people a chance to free
themselves from continued oppression and contribute toward
sustainable development of the continent, Situla said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the leaders involved in armed conflicts to resolve
their differences through dialog in order to give peace a chance.
</P>
<P>
He commended Zambian President Frederick Chiluba for his
tireless efforts in trying to bring peace to the Democratic
Republic of the Congo and expressed hope that the cease-fire which
was signed on July 10 in Lusaka would be successfully implemented.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
