<HEADLINE> Cholera Hits Uganda's Capital Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Eight people have been admitted
to Mulago hospital's cholera treatment center following another
outbreak of the epidemic in Uganda's capital city Kampala.
</P>
<P>
This cholera outbreak was mainly blamed on the current heavy
rains, Saturday's Monitor newspaper quoted Cholera Camp Manager
Bwire Godfrey as saying.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned the public to take precautionary measures when
handling food and drinks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kampala District Health Director Misaki Mubiru has
deployed health workers to sensitize residents on cleanliness,
saying if the situation worsens, all unhygienic eating and
drinking places would be closed.
</P>
<P>
A total of 153 Ugandans have died of cholera in the country so
far this year. About 3,053 cholera cases have been reported since
the beginning of 1999, bringing the cumulative number to 52,216
since the last epidemic outbreak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
