<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Becomes More Popular in Mideast: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Internet is gaining a
wider popular appeal among communities in the Middle East,
drawing more users from lower educational backgrounds and entering
more homes than offices, a study said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year and a half, the number of Internet users in
the region who hold only a high-school diploma or less has
dramatically increased from 17 percent to 27 percent, said the
study issued by Internet Arab World magazine.
</P>
<P>
The increase has come entirely from new adult users, it added.
</P>
<P>
The users with an undergraduate university degree remained
dominant at 58.6 percent among the Internet users in the Arab
world, which are estimated at 1.1 million now.
</P>
<P>
Holders of PhDs and master's degree account for 14.5 percent of
1,000 surveyed, which was a drop of about 5 percent over 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The study, made in cooperation with DITnet, is based on a user
profile survey conducted on-line for the second time in a year and
a half.
</P>
<P>
One of the significant outcomes of the survey is that an
increasing number of users are spending more time on the Internet
at home than in office.
</P>
<P>
The majority of respondents, 72 percent, said home was the
primary place where they accessed the Internet, while only 22
percent said it was the office.
</P>
<P>
Many factors are contributing to the increasing popularity of
the Internet among Arab users, which include falling rates of
Internet access that are encouraging more people to subscribe at
home, and an increasing awareness of the benefits and various
services available on-line.
</P>
<P>
The study also showed that the average age of Internet users in
the Arab world had, meanwhile, increased by one year to reach 30,
but remained younger than the global average, which stands at 33.
</P>
<P>
The Internet community in the Arab world remained
overhelmingly dominated by men, with only a marginal increase in
women users in the sample from 4.2 percent to 6 percent, the study
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
