<HEADLINE> Quake Rocks Indonesian Capital, West Java </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A tectonic earthquake measuring
6.0 on the Richter scale jolted Jakarta, Lampung, Bengkulu and
West Java provinces at 07:16 a.m. local time on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The central Meteorological and Geophysical Agency said in its
statement here that the quake's epicenter was located in the Sunda
Straits, about 350 kilometers west of Jakarta and 80 kilometers
beneath the sea surface.
</P>
<P>
In Jakarta, several people were going out their office during
the quake, particularly those whose office were in high buildings.
</P>
<P>
In Lampung, according to the Antara News Agency, the quake
caused panic-stricken residents to stay outdoors.
</P>
<P>
So far, there are no reports of damage or casualties.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, a quake measuring 5.7 on the Richter scale
rocked Kupang, capital of East Nusa Tenggara, while the previous
day (August 12) a quake measuring 6.0 on the Richter scale also
jolted the central Sulawesi town of Luwuk.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, comprising thousands of islands which are part of
the so-called "Pacific Ring of Fire," is prone to earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
In February 1994, Lampung suffered serious damage from
earthquakes, causing 207 people to die and thousands of people
injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
