<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Urges African Govts to Control Tobacco Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) is urging African governments to come up with appropriate
laws to control the use of tobacco to avoid tobacco-related
diseases.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Harare Friday, the WHO said that if
nothing is done in the next 20 years, deaths caused by tobacco in
Africa will double and represent nine percent of all deaths.
</P>
<P>
"This can be prevented if African governments pass and enforce
appropriate laws to control the use of tobacco and undertake a
sustained campaign to inform and educate the people about the
dangers of tobacco smoking," the WHO said.
</P>
<P>
The organization said because of intensive advertising
campaigns by the tobacco industry to promote their products,
tobacco smoking had reached epidemic proportions and was fast
becoming a major public health hazard in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"Now is the time for Africa to check the tobacco epidemic
before it becomes a much bigger public health problem. We have
enough priority problems already. We should not add tobacco," WHO
regional director for Africa Ebrahim Samba said.
</P>
<P>
He said while some countries may argue that tobacco sustained
their economies, studies by the World Bank and other institutions
had shown that tobacco was bad economics because of its negative
effect on the health of the population.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The social, economic and disease burdens caused by
tobacco far exceed the seeming economic benefits or gains it
provides."
</P>
<P>
Tobacco provides a sizeable portion of the foreign exchange
earnings of some African countries such as Malawi, Tanzania,
Uganda, Kenya, South Africa and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The WHO, under its Tobacco Free Initiative Program, which was
launched last year, provided crop substitution among tobacco
growing nations. The suggested crops were vegetables, flowers,
citrus fruits and cotton, among others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
