<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Temporary Cease-fire in Congo for Immunization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Parties to the conflict in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) have agreed to temporarily lay
down arms to make way for the immunization of over 10 million
children against polio-myelitis, the daily Herald reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The three-phase national immunization program will cover the
whole of the war-ravaged country of about 50 million people.
</P>
<P>
Ebrahim Samba, director of World Health Organization (WHO)
regional office for Africa, said this in Harare Friday.
</P>
<P>
Samba said the warring forces, including Uganda- and
Rwanda-backed rebels, agreed to the temporary cessation of
hostilities after a series of meetings spearheaded by United
Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations, which also involved international partners,
took six months.
</P>
<P>
Belligerents from both sides are taking part in the program,
which is incorporating measles vaccination and administering
vitamin A supplements.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed "Health For Peace", the campaign is part of the WHO's
initiative to clear the world of vaccine-preventable diseases.
</P>
<P>
Samba said to show their commitment, the governments of Rwanda
and Uganda were even sending staff to assist in the program.
</P>
<P>
"The temporary cease-fire has nothing to do with the Lusaka
peace agreement. This is not a political matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
The first phase started Friday and is expected to last at the
weekend. The second phase is planned for September 17 to 19, while
the third is scheduled for October 22 to 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
