<HEADLINE> China resents U.S. Government's allowing the Dalai Lama trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- China voices its strong
resentment and firm opposition with the U.S. government for
allowing the Dalai Lama to visit the United States, Foreign
Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said here today.
</P>
<P>
When commenting on the Dalai Lama's recent trip to New York,
Zhu said China has already made a solemn representation to the U.S.
side.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is an inalienable part of the Chinese territories, and
the Tibet issue is entirely China's internal affairs, which brooks
no interference from any foreign country, Zhu said, adding that
the Dalai lama is not merely a religious figure but a political
exile engaged in the activities of splitting China.
</P>
<P>
"China demands that the U.S. adheres to its stance of
recognizing Tibet as a part of China and not supporting 'the
independence of Tibet', and that it immediately put a halt to its
erroneous acts of interfering in China's internal affairs
concerning the Tibet issue," Zhu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
