<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 06:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Police Warn Against Swindlers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Police departments of the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) have warned the residents against the
tricks of international swindlers who lure people with attractive
"prizes and special offers."
</P>
<P>
Some European-based companies are sending letters to targeted
people in the UAE, informing they have won valuable prizes like
gold ornaments, a house, or a luxury holiday in an expensive
destination, police sources said.
</P>
<P>
"They ask their would-be victims to send certain amounts of
money and the prizes will be sent to them by mail or courier," the
Khaleej Times daily quoted the sources as saying Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of such swindling letters have landed in the
UAE recently, they noted, adding that a massive awareness campaign
has been launched to protect people from the gangs of swindlers.
</P>
<P>
Some letters say the targeted person has won a diamond ring, an
expensive watch, a holiday in a European resort or simply an
amount of money. The tricksters say a small amount is needed for
sending the prize.
</P>
<P>
Other letters, according to crime investigation officers, ask
UAE residents to receive some large amounts of money and then hand
them over to a third party, for the service they could be paid a
good commission.
</P>
<P>
"But the targeted person here would have to pay an initial
amount of money or send his credit card number or bank account
number," police officers said.
</P>
<P>
Many people got shocked when they knew that they had lost
their hard-earned cash, having fallen victim to these tricks.
</P>
<P>
The countries from which the letters were sent include Spain,
the United States, the U.K. and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"People had called the numbers shown on the letters and found
that they were all incorrect numbers," the officers said.
</P>
<P>
"Some people contacted the embassies of these countries and
discovered for themselves that the offices of these tricksters'
companies did not even exist."
</P>
<P>
The police admit that it is difficult for them to contain
this problem unless people themselves fight the crime by refusing
to accept tricksters' offers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
