<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Stars Rule the Pool in SEA Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Thai swimming stars rule the
pool in Bangar Seri Begawan by winning the highest number of golds
in the swimming competition of the 20th Southeast Asian (SEA)
Games.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom's swimmers rounded off the swimming action, which
concluded Friday night, by winning two of the six finals on the
day, while the country's latest sensation, Pilin Techakittiranan,
came very close to beating Singapore's Golden Girl Joscelin Yeo in
the bid to be the fastest woman swimmer in the region.
</P>
<P>
Pilin, a 16-year-old sweat-smiling student, won six golds for
her country, including three individual ones in 200m, 400m and
800m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
However, Singapore's Yeo shines more brightly as she also won
six golds, but all individuals and all in new Games record.
</P>
<P>
The Thais topped the six-day competition, garnering 13 golds,
eight silvers and six bronze, while Singapore, with seven golds,
10 silvers and nine bronze, pipped Malaysia, which grabbed seven
golds, eight silvers and four bronze, with a higher number of
silvers.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia had five golds, three silvers and 10 bronze.
</P>
<P>
The other nations failed to win a single medal in the event.
</P>
</TEXT>
