<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deflationary Pressure Eased In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The decline in China's price
indices eased off a little last month, raising hopes that the
country's economy is climbing out of its deflationary cycle, today
's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The retail price index (RPI), negative since October 1997,
dipped 2.6 percent in July on a year-on-year basis, according to
the National Bureau of Statistics. The RPI for the year's first
seven months was down 3.1 percent after falling 3.2 percent in the
first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The broader consumer price index (CPI), which also covers
services, was 1.4 percent down in July, averaging minus 1.7
percent for the first seven months. The CPI dropped 1.8 percent
during the January-June period.
</P>
<P>
The bureau attributed the improvement of the indices in July to
a recovery in the prices of meat, poultry and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales totaled 238 billion yuan (28.7 billion US dollars)
in July, up 5.6 percent over the same month of last year. The
growth rate was unchanged from June.
</P>
<P>
The government has said it plans to raise the salaries of civil
servants and increase benefits for pensioners and workers laid off
from state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Growth in public sector fixed assets investment was the major
force driving the economy in the second half of last year and the
first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The government has said it will expand spending in the second
half of the year to give a fresh stimulus to the economy. But the
volume of spending has not yet been announced.
</P>
<P>
The recovery in the foreign trade sector would also assist the
government in its efforts to prevent economic growth from slowing
further.
</P>
<P>
China's exports totaled 17.3 billion US dollars in July, up 7.5
percent over the same month of 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
