<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- European stock markets closed higher Friday, lifted
by a lower-than-expected 0.2 percent rise in the July U.S.
producer price index.
</P>
<P>
The UK's FTSE 100 index, which had been trading down 24 points
before the release of the U.S. producer price figures, rebounded
to close up 1.49 percent, or 91.8 points, at 6,245.1.
</P>
<P>
Strong support came from Wall Street where the Dow index was up
around 135 points as the London session ended its third successive
positive close. (Europe-Stocks
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Crude oil prices rallied to a 22-month peak of 21 U.S.
dollars a barrel Friday, buoyed by Nigerian supply disruption,
declines in U.S. oil stockpiles and OPEC output restraint.
</P>
<P>
London September futures for Britain's Brent crude touched the
psychological 21 U.S. dollar level, its highest since October 9,
1997, before dropping back to 20.88 U.S. dollars for a 39 cent
gain. (Markets-Oil
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- World sugar production will surpass demand
for the fifth consecutive season in 1999-2000 because of the
record harvest in Brazil, the "Gazeta Mercantil" newspaper
reported on Friday. (Brazil-World-Sugar Output)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavia's gross domestic product in 1999 is
expected to drop by 23.6 percent from the level of last year, said
Milorad Filipovic, head of the Yugoslav Agency for Development and
Economic Policy told the press Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government, which has just been reshuffled, will try to
curb the year-on-year inflation below 35.2 percent at the end of
the year and keep the dinar exchange rate stable, he said. (
Yugoslavia-Economy) 
</P>
