<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> JP Morgan Minimizes Crisis Risk in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 13 (Xinhua) -- International investment
firm JP Morgan considers it is "not very probable" that an
economic crisis would follow the change of government in Mexico in
2000.
</P>
<P>
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo's financial strategy
strengthened the economy of his country and reduced its
vulnerability toward the flight of foreign capital, said the JP
Morgan's financial consulting institution in an analysis dated in
July and published Friday in the Mexican capital.
</P>
<P>
The changes of government have been characterized for the last
25 years by big devaluation that evaporated the savings of the
people, increased the foreign debt of businessmen, raised
inflation and reduced the growth of the nation.
</P>
<P>
The institution pointed as favorable factors for the Mexican
economy a flexible rate of exchange as well as the reduction of
the proportion of the current account deficit to the gross
domestic product from 5 percent during the third four-month period
of 1998 to 2.8 percent during the first four-month period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Other positive measures are the guarantees of foreign financing
of 17 billion U.S. dollars, including International Monetary Fund
resources, and the strengthening of the local banking system.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican economy "starts to recover" after the "mini
recession" at the end of 1998 and the foreign resources will
permit it to dampen any eventual flight of capital, which would
contain any devaluation, it added.
</P>
<P>
JP Morgan said elections scheduled for July 2 next year when
the next Mexican president will come out will be "the most
transparent and competitive of the last 70 years" in the country.
</P>
<P>
The institution said that there are minor risks of financial
speculation in the political environment in Mexico and that the
only risk factor for the Mexican economy is the weakness of the
banking system of the country.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo said at the beginning of the year that he would deliver
"clear accounts" to his successor, referring to the fact that 20
days after his assumption of office, a flight of capital inherited
from the previous government caused an economic crisis in December
of 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
