<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hanoi Strives to Halt Increase in HIV/AIDS Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Authorities in Vietnam's capital
has been making great efforts to halt an alarming increase in
HIV/AIDS cases by distributing thousands of condoms, syringes,
rubber gloves and informational brochures, Vietnam News reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of Hanoi health authorities, Hanoi has
738 HIV carriers detected. Of them, 29 had developed AIDS and nine
had died.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the number of HIV/AIDS carriers, the capital city now
ranks fifth among Vietnam's 61 provinces and cities after Ho Chi
Minh City and Quang Ninh, Khanh Hoa and Hai Phong provinces.
</P>
<P>
HIV/AIDS carriers have been detected in 125 of Hanoi's 228
wards and communes and most of the newly detected patients are
drug addicts aged between 13 and 29. In some families, all their
members have contracted HIV/AIDS. And worse still, in some cases,
all members in a family have died of the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
Hanoi's HIV/AIDS Committee has instructed districts, communes,
relevant agencies and mass organizations to promote HIV/AIDS
prevention activities. HIV/AIDS preventive measures now dominate
the city's information dissemination.
</P>
<P>
As many as 10,000 glass syringes were given to drug addicts,
30,000 condoms were issued to people in the high risk group, and
120,000 plastic syringes and 10,000 pairs of rubber gloves were
distributed to medical establishments. Up to 73 percent of
HIV/AIDS carriers in the city are being monitored.
</P>
<P>
More than 14,500 HIV/AIDS carriers had been detected in Vietnam
by July 31. The figure included 2,736 AIDS patients and 1,341
people who have died of AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
