<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Simplifies Passport Procedures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Beijing residents planning tours
abroad can now apply for personal passports with a certificate
proving they have at least 4,000 U.S. dollars in the bank, China
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
In the past, all personal passport applicants were required to
provide letters of invitation and financial guarantees from their
relatives and friends abroad, to ensure they had someone to turn
to for help if they encountered problems during their trip.
</P>
<P>
This will henceforth only be required when emigration officials
deem it necessary, said Liu Chengshe, an official with the Exit
and Entry Administration Division of the Beijing Public Security
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Passports will be valid for five years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bureau has also simplified the procedures for
payment of passport and service charges as well as for passport
applications for those leaving the country on business.
</P>
<P>
The bureau handled more than 90,000 applications in the first
six months, some 30,000 more than the same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Climate Changes to Harm Central America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Central America is highly
vulnerable to climate changes and will suffer the consequent
effects in the coming century, Christina Figueres, Director of the
American Sustainable Development Center said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Figueres said the sea level could rise between 15 and 95
centimeters in the next 100 years, threatening the coast
settlements.
</P>
<P>
"The layer of the atmosphere that produces the greenhouse
effect has undergone concentration of gases of 30 percent in the
last 100 years, which might raise the temperature of the Earth,"
said the environmentalist in an interview with the RPC Radio.
</P>
<P>
The Earth will undergo the greenhouse effect resulting from the
concentration of gases and the temperature of the planet will rise
1 to 3.5 degrees centigrade in the next 100 years, said Figueres.
</P>
<P>
The industrialization in the countries of the northern
hemisphere and the irresponsible deforestation in the developing
countries are to blame for this climate change, she said.
</P>
<P>
Both activities have brought about carbon dioxide emissions,
which form a blanket around the Earth and retain the heat of the
sun radiation.
</P>
<P>
"These phenomena cause a rise in the planet's temperature,
which has many effects," such as the dangerous rise of the sea
level, droughts, hurricanes, storms and the migration of
agricultural zones, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Director said that the concentration of the gases that
produce greenhouse effect could increase the incidence of
diseases such as malaria and dengue in the region.  
