<DOCNO> XIE19990814.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lankan Economy Displays Resilience in 1998: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's economy displayed
considerable resilience in 1998 despite many hiccups caused by
external issues, the Securities and Exchange Commission of Sri
Lanka said in its annual report released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
These included the East Asian currency crisis, a decline in
Russian tea purchases and Indo-Pakistan nuclear tests, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
"The external sector performed reasonably well in 1998 to post
a positive balance of payment out-turn. Both exports and imports
recorded much lower increases, exports by 2.1 percent and imports
by 0.9 percent as compared with increases of 13 percent and 8
percent respectively in 1997," it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said there were positive developments in foreign
direct investment (FDI) despite lesser official capital flows,
lower privatization proceeds and negative portfolio flows.
</P>
<P>
"According to estimates, the FDI flows increased from 129
million U.S. dollars in 1997 to 137 million dollars in 1998."
</P>
<P>
Tea prices, which remained buoyant for a few years, continued
to remain high during the first half of the year, but slipped in
the second half following the collapse of the Russian market.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, export earnings from tea showed only a modest
growth of eight percent.
</P>
<P>
Under the impact of intense competition from East Asian
countries whose currencies depreciated sharply in the wake of the
Asian financial crisis, international prices for rubber and
coconut declined in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Thus export earnings from rubber and coconut dropped by 45
percent and 32 percent in U.S. dollar terms.
</P>
<P>
The report added that Sri Lanka's industrial exports increased
by 3.1 percent in 1998 compared with an earnings growth of 14
percent recorded in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The major cause for the slow growth in industrial exports was a
drop in the value of petroleum product exports and other
industrial exports by 24.7 percent and 21.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the downturn in commodity prices in the
international markets following the recession in East Asian
countries helped Sri Lanka contain its import bill.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the trade deficit is estimated to have declined
from 1,225 million dollars in 1997 to 1,157 million dollars in
1998, a drop of 5.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
