<HEADLINE> Popular Colombian Satirist Killed by Gunmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's popular
satirist and journalist Jaime Garzon was killed by two gunmen on
his way to work early Friday as the country's bumpy peace process
took its latest toll.
</P>
<P>
Colleagues said Garzon had received threats from right-wing
paramilitary groups who did not like his sympathetic stand toward
the left-wing rebels. He had helped organize rebel news
conferences and served as an intermediary between guerrillas and
the families of kidnap victims.
</P>
<P>
The 40-year-old journalist, comic and political activist, was
shot in the head several times when he was pulling his jeep to the
offices of Radionet, where he worked as a morning host, police
sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to a witness, one of the gunmen got off a motorcycle
and shot Garzon point blank five times.
</P>
<P>
President Andres Pastrana condemned the assassination and
ordered police to hunt down the killers as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"It was not just that he made us laugh. Jaime in large part
identified with the sentiments of Colombians, with what we were
thinking," Pastrana said.
</P>
<P>
The killing added to a rising wave of paramilitary, guerrilla
and drug trafficking violence as the country struggles hard along
the road to national reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
