<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diabetes Claims 85,000 Lives Annually in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Diabetes, a pandemic disease
in Latin America, is claiming an average of 85,000 lives a year in
the region, specialists said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Over 40 percent of the diabetes-related deaths occur in Mexico,
they said at an updating course on diabetes being held in the 21st
Century National Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
The control of this incurable malady improves with the
education of the patients and their family as well as with the
adequate supply of medicines, they said.
</P>
<P>
Around the world, 140 million people suffer this disease and
millions of them lack adequate assistance, they added.
</P>
<P>
The updating course is attended by medical doctors and
specialists, among them the members of the Foundation for the
Insuline-Dependent Diabetic Patient, a private organization.
</P>
<P>
Diabetes is a mortal disease that is characterized by an excess
of sugar in the blood and causes the patients' incontinence,
gastric trouble, blindness and headache. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
