<HEADLINE> Gullit Charged by FA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Newcastle manager Ruud Gullit's
problems continued to pile up as the Football Association charged
him with misconduct.
</P>
<P>
The Dutchman, whose side has lost their opening two games of
the season, was angered by referee Uriah Rennie's decision to
dismiss his captain Alan Shearer during last Saturday's 1-0 defeat
by Aston Villa. Shearer was sent off for two bookable offences
after an innocuous challenge with Villa defender Colin Calderwood,
but Gullit was incensed and had to be forcibly restrained from
running on to the field by counterpart John Gregory.
</P>
<P>
Gullit blasted Rennie after the game and was alleged to have
made comments to the Sheffield match official after the game, and
now the FA have confirmed that they have charged Gullit with
misconduct after receiving the referee's match report.
</P>
<P>
"Ruud Gullit has been charged with misconduct for alleged
comments made to Uriah Rennie at the end of last Saturday's game,"
FA spokesman Steve Double said. "He has 14 days to respond."
</P>
<P>
But Double added that the investigation into Villa boss Gregory,
who was also mentioned by Rennie in his report, was still
continuing.
</P>
<P>
"Further investigation into that is going on," Double said.
</P>
<P>
Shearer had appealed for Rennie to re-consider his decision
after he and nearby Villa players were bemused by the second
yellow card.
</P>
<P>
But Rennie stood firm and upheld his judgement and insisted
that Shearer had been dismissed for "persistent misconduct."
</P>
