<HEADLINE> Joscelin Yeo Wins Sixth Gold at SEA Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Singapore swimmer
Joscelin Yeo overcame an elbow injury to win two more gold medals
at the 20th Southeast Asian Games in Brunei on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old easily won both the women's 50m freestyle and
400m medley finals to finish the meet with six individual titles.
</P>
<P>
Yeo won the 50m freestyle sprint in 26.23 seconds, trimming 0.
43 off her own record, then the medley in 4 minutes 51.87, 1.42
inside the old mark held by Thailand's Ravee Intporn-Udom.
</P>
<P>
Yeo was almost forced out of the competition after aggravating
an elbow injury on Tuesday. She pulled out of her three scheduled
events on Wednesday but returned to the pool on Friday after two
days rest.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Praphalsal Minpraphal also set a Games record of 2:
14.54 in the women's 200m butterfly while Indonesia's Albert
Sutanto lowered the men's 200m butterfly mark to 2:02.06.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia overtook Thailand at the head of the medals standings
after winning another five golds on Friday.
</P>
<P>
They now have 50 with just two days of competition remaining
with Thailand on 49 and Indonesia 38. 
</P>
