<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Military Fortification Discovered In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists have discovered
a number of military buildings dating back to the Western Han
Dynasty (206 B.C. - A.D. 24), south of the Yellow River in Xin'an
County, in Central China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
The site is 178 meters long from south to north and 29 meters
wide from east to west, with walls, cornerstones, and alleyways.
There are many tiles with the Chinese character "Guan" (which
means "fort" or "pass" in the Chinese language) on them that have
been found at the spot that local archeologists say were specially
used for military forts.
</P>
<P>
The archeologists say they believe the site was part of a
central Chinese military fort at Hanguguan and might have been
used as a storehouse for food or weapons.
</P>
<P>
The discovery indicates that Hanguguan was not only a military
fort but also the main section of a system of fortifications that
ran to the Yellow River, the archeologists say, and it provides
valuable materials for the study of the economy, military affairs
and transportation during the ancient Han Dynasty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
