<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Sugar Output to Surpass Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- World sugar production
will surpass demand for the fifth consecutive season in 1999-2000,
because of the record harvest in Brazil, the "Gazeta Mercantil"
newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that production in Brazil, the world's
largest sugar producer, could reach 20.9 million tons during this
season against the 19.2 million tons in the previous season.
</P>
<P>
World sugar output will be 135.7 million tons in the 1999-2000
season, compared to the 132 million tons in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
"Gazeta Mercantil" also forecast that world demand will rise to
127 million tons this season, against 124.7 million tons in 1998-
99.
</P>
<P>
Sugar prices fell last May in the world market to their lowest
level in the last 14 years due to excess supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
