<HEADLINE> Sampras, Agassi Reach Semi-finals at ATP Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- World No. 1 American Pete
Sampras cruised into the semi-finals of the $2.2 million ATP
Championship today with an easy victory over nemesis Richard
Krajicek of the Netherlands in Cincinnati, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who turned 28 on Thursday, posted a 6-4, 6-2 victory
over the seventh-seeded Krajicek, extending his winning streak to
19 matches and setting up a semi-final matchup with countryman
Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, the third seed, won a lengthy third set tiebreak and
advanced with 6-2, 7-6 (12-10) victory over No. 6 Gustavo Kuerten
of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The top-seeded Sampras beat Agassi in straight sets in the
Wimbledon Final on July 4.
</P>
<P>
In another quarter-final match, fourth seed Yevgeny Kafelnikov
of Russia beat Britian's Tim Henman, the fifth seed 7-5, 7-5.
Tonight, second seed Patrick Rafter of Australia faces unseeded
American Michael Chang.
</P>
<P>
Krajicek had won four straight matches over Sampras, last
season's runner-up at this event.
</P>
<P>
"Richard has given me problems throughout my career," Sampras
said. "His game is kind of very similar in our styles of play.
When he gets hot, he is very, very tough to play. I knew he has
had a great record (against me).
</P>
<P>
"It was very close in the beginning," said Krajicek. "We were
pretty equal in the beginning and just whoever was going to take
his chances and also seeing how he has been playing the last
couple of weeks. I think it just happened who was most confident
at the moment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
