<HEADLINE> Bucks Name Ernie Grunfeld New General Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Ernie Grunfeld, who was run
out of New York before the Knicks made their stunning run to the
NBA Finals in the lockout-shortened season, today was named
general manager of the Milwaukee Bucks, replacing Bob Weinhauer.
</P>
<P>
Weinhauer was fired Wednesday, despite helping the Bucks to
their first playoff appearance since 1991. But coach George Karl,
who signed a four-year, $20 million contract with the Bucks before
last season, has a large say in personnel matters and is expected
to form a more cohesive tandem with Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
Grunfeld was relieved of his duties on April 21 as the Knicks
struggled to find any sort of cohesion during the regular season
following the acquisitions of Marcus Camby and Latrell Sprewell
via trades.
</P>
<P>
Despite barely entering the playoffs at 27-23, Grunfeld was
vindicated as the Knicks became the first eighth seed to reach the
NBA Finals, which they lost to the San Antonio Spurs in five games.
</P>
<P>
Grunfeld, 44, had served the Knicks organization for 17 years,
including the last eight-plus in the front office. He started as
director of administration in 1990 and continually was promoted to
president and general manager midway through the 1995-96 season.
</P>
<P>
The Bucks lost free agents Dell Curry and Michael Curry to
Toronto and Detroit, but re-sign veteran guard Haywoode Workman.
</P>
<P>
Grunfeld had a nine-year NBA playing career that ended with the
Knicks in the 1985-86 season. He also served within the
organization as a broadcaster and coach before joining the front
office before the 1990-91 season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
