<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Updates with more contents) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The wholesale prices
increased just 0.2 percent in July because a big jump in energy
prices overwhelmed a sharp drop in food costs, the Labor
Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The July's advance in the Producer Price Index matched the 0.2
percent rise in May. It was slightly better than expected. Many
analysts had been anticipating that the prices would rise 0.3
percent in July. June's prices had actually fallen 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the moderate gain in wholesale prices, if matched
at the consumer level, could ease concerns somewhat at the Federal
Reserve about a potential breakout of inflation.
</P>
<P>
Financial markets were buoyed by the better-than-expected
news on inflation. The bond market rallied, pushing the yield
down on Treasury's 30-year bonds, and Dow Jones industrial
average closed up 184.26 points at 10,973.65.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, wholesale prices have been rising at an
annual rate of 1.7 percent, compared to no change for all of 1998.
The rise in this year's wholesale prices is coming from big jump
in energy costs, which had been falling for much of 1998.
</P>
<P>
For July, energy costs picked up 3.4 percent, led by 12.7
percent increase in gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
The July gain in gasoline prices was the largest since a 26
percent surge in April, which helped push overall wholesale prices
up by 0.5 percent that month, the biggest increase this year. That
gain plus an even bigger rise in consumer prices in April put the
Fed on inflation alert and led to a June 30 increase in a key Fed
interest rate.
</P>
<P>
The 3.4 percent rise in energy costs in July was partially
offset by a 0.9 percent drop in food prices. Beef prices, which
had risen sharply in June, declined by 3.4 percent in July, the
biggest one-month drop since February 1997.
</P>
<P>
If excluding the volatile energy and food categories,
wholesales prices were unchanged in July, after having fallen 0.2
percent in June.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
