<HEADLINE> IFC Invests in Turkish Tractor Manufacturer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) announced Friday that it will lend 35 million
U.S. dollars to Uzel Makina Sanayi A.S. of Turkey to help the
tractor maker modernize.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to move the company's manufacturing
plant from a crowded district of Istanbul to Duzce, about 210
kilometers away, and increase productivity and capacity.
</P>
<P>
Uzel Makina Sanayi produces agricultural tractors, diesel
engines and automotive parts. The company was established in 1930
as a carriage manufacturer, and later started manufacturing
automotive components. It began producing tractors in 1962.
</P>
<P>
Uzel Makina Sanayi is 85 percent owned by members of the Uzel
family through a holding company, and the remaining 15 percent of
the shares are traded on the Istanbul Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The total costs of the project are 98 million dollars. IFC's
investment includes a loan of 20 million dollars for its own
account and a syndicated loan of 15 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The mission of IFC, a member of the World Bank Group, is to
promote private sector investment in developing countries, which
will reduce poverty and improve people's lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
